French church fire in Nantes: parish volunteers admit arson peace
According to foreign media reports, on July 18, the religious historical buildings of Nantes, France, the famous St. Peter and St Paul's Cathedral, were severely damaged in a fire, and the large organ was completely destroyed.
On the 26th local time, Nantes prosecutors announced that a parish volunteer in charge of defending the cathedral had been charged with "arson destruction".
He admitted that he had set fire to the church.
Senas, the local prosecutor, said the 39-year-old parish volunteer from Rwanda admitted to igniting three places in the cathedral at night.
The man’s lawyer said the arsonists now regretted doing such a thing.
A few years ago, he entered France through the way of refuge, was sheltered in the parish where the fire occurred, and was taken in into the church.
The prosecution noted that recently, he tried to renew his visa and was in dialogue with the police.
But the church said it still couldn't believe that this usually very kind, smiling believer, but not much to talk about, will destroy the church he loves so much.
On the day of the July 18 fire, the volunteer had already received a police inquiry and investigation because of the logical problem in the narrative, but he was later released.
Firefighters are on the scene for rescue.
On the evening of the 25th, as a professional engineer at the laboratory of the Central Police in Paris obtained new evidence, the person was again arraigned.
This time, the man admitted to his act of arson.
If convicted of intentional arson damage, the suspect could face 10 years in prison and a fine of 150,000 euros.
According to the report, the fire caused serious damage to the St. Pierre and St. Paul's Cathedral, the organ inside the church was completely destroyed, and the stained glass windows behind the organ were also severely damaged.
Brune, the chief architect of the French Historic Preservation, said it was conservatively estimated that the restoration of the cathedral in Nantes would take at least three years.
Comprehensive news: US unilateralism undermines bilateral relations International public opinion supports China's counter-measures against the United States
