Poland to withdraw from European treaty to prevent violence against women
Poland's justice ministry said Saturday it will take steps to withdraw from the European treaty on violence against women next week.
Poland’s right-wing government cabinet says the treaty requires schools to teach students about gender issues and trample on the rights of their parents.
Poland’s Justice Minister Joblow told a news conference that his Ministry of Justice would ask the Ministry of Labour and Family Monday to begin withdrawing from the treaty.
The treaty is also known as the Istanbul Convention.
According to Gioblo, “the treaty contains elements of a morphological nature that we consider to be harmful”.
Poland’s ruling Law and Justice Party, together with its governing coalition partners, has a close alliance with the Roman Catholic Church and promotes a conservative social agenda.
Polish President Duda made hostility to gay rights one of the main topics during his successful re-election campaign this month.
On Friday, thousands of Poles, most of them women, staged protests against the withdrawal from the convention in Warsaw and in some other cities.
One of the organizers of the protests, Lempat, said in a protest march in Warsaw that “the purpose of withdrawing from the treaty is to legalize domestic violence.”
Some protesters held banners that read “The Law and Justice Party is a woman’s hell.”
The Law and Justice Party has long complained about the Istanbul Convention.
Poland’s former centrist government ratified the convention in 2015.
The Law and Justice party government said the treaty did not respect religion and required liberal social policies to be taught in schools.
So far, the party has not decided to withdraw from the convention.
(According to Reuters)
