FAA orders to check 2,000 Boeing passenger planes
The Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) issued an emergency airworthiness directive on the 24th, requiring emergency inspections of about 2,000 Boeing 737NG and 737 Classic passenger aircraft registered in the United States, because the air check valve of the above passenger aircraft may cause engine air parking after corrosion.
The FAA said it had received four reports of air-parking of engines for 737NG and 737 Classic aircraft so far, leading to an emergency inspection request for passenger aircraft that had been parked for seven days or more and fewer than 11 flights since re-entry.
The Federal Aviation Administration warned that if the fifth-class check-up valve of all two engines of the passenger plane is corroded, it may die in the open position, causing the passenger to completely lose power and unable to restart the engine.
The aviation regulator ordered that once the check valve is found to be corroded, the airline operator must replace the key component before the passenger plane is put into service again.
Boeing later in the day responded that the outbreak of the new crown epidemic led to a decrease in travel demand, many passenger aircraft were sealed or less used, "the check valve is more likely to be corroded."
Boeing also said that it has recommended that the airline operator inspect the passenger aircraft involved in the order, and if the problem is found, Boeing will provide assistance in overhauling and replacing the check valve.
The Associated Press reported that passenger aircraft under the major U.S. airlines usually fly multiple times a day, but after the outbreak of the new crown epidemic, a large number of passenger aircraft were grounded; as passenger travel demand has recently grown slowly, some passenger aircraft have returned to operation.
The FAA did not release details of four air parking reports.
Alaska Airlines revealed one of the incidents later on the 24th.
The airliner said in a statement that on its flight from Seattle, Washington, to Austin, Texas, on July 15, an engine suddenly turned off and the passenger plane finally made an emergency landing at Austin airport.
Alaska Airlines said it had replaced the aircraft's engine and had inspected the engines of six aircraft in accordance with FAA instructions.
American Airlines, United Airlines and Southwest Airlines said on the 24th that their passenger aircraft did not have a fire with the engine associated with the air check valve.
Four of the American Airlines aircraft will be inspected, and 28 of United Airlines' aircraft will be inspected.
Delta said it would check its 20 planes, but did not say whether there had been a engine shutdown.
According to multiple media reports, the FAA's emergency airworthiness directive is another shock to Boeing.
Lion Air Indonesia and Ethiopian Airlines each lost 346 deaths in October 2018 and March 2019, respectively.
The series of passenger planes was subsequently grounded worldwide, discontinued in January this year, and resumed production in May.
Federal Aviation Administrator Steve Dixon admitted in June that the FAA had “made a mistake” in regulating Boeing over the 737 MAX.
