Lewis family: John Lewis is a fighter for the weakest fight
U.S. Congressman and civil rights fighter John Lewis was remembered as a “warrie for the weakest” at his memorial service on Saturday (July 25).
Lewis' public memorial service began Saturday in Alabama.
There were two memorial services on the first day.
At a public stern memorial service Saturday at the University of Troy in Alabama, Lewis’s five siblings and a nephew talked about him as a loving, surging, family-heavy man.
Lewis' youngest brother, Henry "Grant" Lewis, said in the meeting: "He has devoted his life to helping others."
Samuel Lewis said his mother had warned John "not to get in trouble, not to get into trouble."
He added that John did not heed his mother’s warning, saying, “We all know that John always gets into trouble, he’s always in trouble, but that’s because it’s right, it’s a good trouble.”
Lewis’s siblings reminded the people at the memorial that John’s most famous argument was to create “good trouble,” that is, to avoid stirring up trouble for the sake of justice.
John had applied to Troy University in Troy, Alabama, where he was born, but Troy University, which was all white at the time, rejected his application for admission.
John Lewis, who preached the gospel against the chickens on his farm as a child, eventually earned a degree in religion and philosophy from Fisk University.
Years later, the University of Troy awarded Lewis an honorary doctorate.
Senator Doug Jones, from Alabama, said the current protesters are “protesting peacefully and non-violently,” as Lewis did in the civil rights movement.
Jones said: "Even if President Trump beats a boatman and calls all the protesters a thug, he is wrong.
The protestors are patriots who want the United States to move toward a more equal nation.”
A series of six-day events in honor of Lewis will culminate this week at his funeral in Georgia.
Lewis’s coffin was parked Saturday at a public memorial at the University of Troy, where people came to pay tribute to the civil rights pioneer.
Late Saturday, a private ceremony paid tribute to him in a small church in Selma, Alabama, followed by an open memorial service.
On Sunday, Lewis' body will pass through Selma's Edmund Pettus Bridge.
In 1965, he and the demonstrators who demanded the right to vote of blacks were beaten by Alabama police in front of the bridge, and the police also cast tear gas on the demonstrators.
Lewis was nearly killed.
It was later called Bloody Sunday.
