APEC member trade ministers say will accelerate regional economic recovery - Xinhua
KUALA LUMPUR, July 25 (Xinhua) -- A video conference of trade ministers of APEC members was held on July 25, pledging to work to reduce the impact of the new coronavirus epidemic on the region's economy and accelerate the realization of a resilient, sustainable and inclusive regional economic recovery.
The meeting was hosted by Malaysia, the host of this year’s APEC Economic Leaders’ Meeting.
The APEC member trade ministers recognized the importance of a free, open, fair, non-discriminatory, transparent and predictable trade and investment environment to drive economic recovery at this challenging time.
The parties committed to ensure that the emergency measures taken to respond to the outbreak are targeted, appropriate, transparent and temporary, without creating unnecessary trade barriers and disrupting global supply chains, while complying with World Trade Organization rules.
In his statement, APEC member trade ministers pledged to strengthen cooperation to promote the necessary flow of goods and services, promote connectivity by strengthening supply chain resilience, and minimize disruptions to the flow of medical supplies, food and agricultural products in response to the epidemic.
APEC member trade ministers agreed on the need to discuss how to reduce non-tariff barriers that restrict trade in essential goods, and reiterated their commitment to promoting the necessary cross-border movement of people without affecting measures taken to stop the spread of the epidemic.
The Conference also issued a declaration on promoting the circulation of essential commodities.
Economies will ensure that their trade measures to respond to the outbreak are in line with WTO regulations, and commit to take action to reduce non-tariff barriers to trade and trade promotion to facilitate the flow of goods necessary under the epidemic.
Malaysia's Minister of International Trade and Industry Azmin Ali said that despite the impact of the epidemic, Malaysia is still committed to promoting the success of this year's APEC meeting, and the work of formulating the vision of APEC cooperation after 2020 is proceeding in an orderly manner.
Malaysia has agreed to hold APEC-related meetings by video, but does not rule out the possibility of scheduling entity meetings at the end of the APEC Economic Leaders’ Meeting.
