In this regard, the school argued that the school has set up a protective network in the playground, and posted management regulations, training notices, told the entrance to the playground to maintain a safe distance from the training ground and remind them to pay attention to their own safety, the plaintiff can not prove that the school "has not fulfilled the safety and security obligations", so do not agree to compensation.
After the court hearing, it was found that the university involved in the incident was free of charge to the public, and although the school had a safety and security obligation for the management of the playground, this security obligation only needed to meet the general duty of care.
At the time of the incident, the school set up a protective network in the playground, and has fulfilled its appropriate safety and security obligations, and Chen also compensated Xiaowen with more than 2,000 yuan for medical expenses, transportation costs and other losses in accordance with the compensation agreement previously reached, and the two sides agreed to resolve the dispute one-time.
Afterwards, Xiao Wen's parents once again claimed the school's compensation, and the court ruled that all the plaintiff's claims were rejected by the court.
After the verdict, neither side appealed and the sentence has now entered into force.
According to Article 37 of China's Tort Liability Law, the school, as the administrator of a public place, has the obligation to ensure safety and security; in the case of the third party's behavior causing damage to others, the third party bears the tort liability, and the public place manager who fails to meet the safety and security obligations shall bear the corresponding supplementary liability.
The judge said that because, as a manager of a public place, it is most likely to understand the actual situation of the entire place, foresee the possible dangers and damage, so that it is most likely to take the necessary measures to prevent the occurrence of loss or reduce the extent of damage, and to avoid and mitigate the lowest cost of damage, so the law stipulates that it is responsible for the corresponding security obligations to engage in social activities.
In this case, for the unspecified entrants in the playground, which is free to the public, the security obligations of the school shall be commensurate with the social activities it is engaged in, in particular, mainly to take basic security measures and have the obligation to inform hidden dangers.
In judicial practice, it is not advisable to impose excessive security obligations on public place managers.
If the school has adopted a protective network and has fulfilled its obligation to inform, it can be determined that the school is not at fault and should not bear legal responsibility.
In addition, for the third party infringement, even if the school and other public places managers did not meet the safety and security obligations, the responsibility is also as a supplement to the damage, according to the latest promulgation of the civil code, the manager to bear the supplementary responsibility, can also be recovered to the third party.
Therefore, in such accidents, the victim should no longer expand the scope of the claim after receiving compensation from the direct infringer.
