Israel to step up repeated prevention and control of the epidemic
At the beginning of the outbreak of the new crown pneumonia epidemic, Israel's prevention and control measures were effective.
However, with the gradual lifting of the ban on prevention and control measures, the number of confirmed cases of new crown pneumonia in Israel has recently increased significantly, and the Israeli government has taken emergency measures to strengthen the prevention and control of the epidemic.
On February 28, the first case of new crown pneumonia was confirmed in Israel, in order to quickly close all ports of entry and exit, suspend non-essential industries, change schools to online classes, restrict public transportation and non-essential social activities, lock down cities with severe epidemics, and jointly maintain prevention and control measures for military and police.
This series of measures quickly achieved positive results, and by mid-May, the number of new confirmed cases of new crown pneumonia in Israel fell to single digits.
With the control of the epidemic, Israel's prevention and control measures have been completely unsealed, and since June, the number of new diagnoses of new crown pneumonia has gradually rebounded.
Especially after entering July, the spread of the epidemic has been accelerating.
In recent days, there have been more than 1,500 new cases in Israel for eight days, and as of July 25, the number of new cases on that day reached 916.
As of July 25, there had been 59,745 confirmed cases and 448 deaths in Israel.
In the face of the rapid rebound of the epidemic, the Israeli government has repeatedly taken emergency measures to strengthen the prevention and control of the epidemic.
On July 6, after the number of confirmed cases exceeded 30,000, the Israeli government closed public entertainment venues such as gyms, swimming pools, bars, nightclubs, etc., and introduced a policy to restrict public transportation, which stipulates that the passengers of each bus should not exceed 20 people.
On the 17th, the Israeli government announced a series of new restrictions, including the implementation of the "closed city" on weekends, which stipulate the implementation of the "closed city" from 1700 hours every Friday to 5 o'clock every week.
During this period, people can go out, but places such as shops, shopping malls, barbershops, beauty salons, libraries, zoos, museums, exhibition halls, swimming pools and tourist attractions will be closed, while basic service venues such as supermarkets and pharmacies will remain open.
At the same time, in all dates and times, gatherings of more than 10 people are prohibited, gyms, studios and other places will be closed, restaurants and cafes will be banned from eating, and only takeaway services will be allowed.
At the same time, the Israeli people have not paid enough attention to the seriousness of the epidemic and have not been able to form a joint effort with the government in fighting the epidemic.
After the recurrence of the epidemic in Israel, many people took to the streets to protest and march because of the impact of government prevention and control measures on their own economic interests.
On July 11, tens of thousands of people held a demonstration in Tel Aviv, arguing that anti-epidemic policies affected the economy.
On the evening of the 21st, thousands of protesters gathered in front of Prime Minister Netanyahu's residence in Jerusalem to protest against Prime Minister Netanyahu's promulgation of prevention and control measures such as banning restaurants and cafes without compensation.
In addition, many people do not comply with the rules of wearing masks and maintaining a safe social distance of two meters when outdoor activities, and in order to avoid fines from being fined by the police for not wearing masks, many people only wear masks on their chins or hang them on their wrists.
During the repeated epidemic, the school was the hardest hit area for the spread of the new coronavirus, and according to the reporter's recent visit to the kindergarten, the kindergarten teachers and students did not wear masks according to government requirements, and did not maintain a safe social distance of two meters to each other, laying a hidden danger for a large number of teachers and students infected with the virus.
Professor Eli Waxman, a member of the Israeli National Security Council's expert advisory group on the fight against the epidemic, said that Israel is moving towards a "dangerous situation", pointing out that the current epidemic prevention and control measures taken by Israel are not enough, and all leisure, entertainment venues and summer schools should be closed to control the further spread of the epidemic.
Waksman said that Israel lacks a general plan to fight the epidemic, and the parliament and government departments should abandon their interests as soon as possible, reach an agreement on the fight against the epidemic, and formulate clear steps to include relevant restrictions in different departments.
